  "prompt": "Is Governor of RBI (Reserve Bank of India) a constitutional post?",
  "response": "No, the Governor of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) is not a constitutional post. The position is established by the Reserve Bank of India Act, 1934, which is a legislative act rather than a provision in the Constitution of India. The Governor is appointed by the President of India and serves a term of three years, although this term can be extended at the discretion of the government. The Governor plays a crucial role in the monetary policy and financial stability of the country, but the post is not defined within the constitutional framework.",
